data.content:
Your `ReportGenerator` has **four** categories of untestable statics — not just file system. Here's the recommended approach for your `net10.0` project:

---

### 1. File System → **`System.IO.Abstractions`** (NuGet)

This is the established library — don't write a custom wrapper.

```
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

Register in DI:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 2. Time → **`TimeProvider`** (built-in on .NET 10)

No package needed:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton(TimeProvider.System);
```

### 3. Environment → Custom minimal wrapper

Only wrap what you actually call (`GetEnvironmentVariable`, `MachineName`):

```csharp
public interface IEnvironmentProvider
{
    string? GetEnvironmentVariable(string variable);
    string MachineName { get; }
}

public sealed class EnvironmentProvider : IEnvironmentProvider
{
    public string? GetEnvironmentVariable(string variable)
        => Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable(variable);
    public string MachineName => Environment.MachineName;
}
```

Register: `builder.Services.AddSingleton<IEnvironmentProvider, EnvironmentProvider>();`

### 4. Refactored `ReportGenerator`

```csharp
public class ReportGenerator(
    IFileSystem fileSystem,
    TimeProvider timeProvider,
    IEnvironmentProvider environment)
{
    public string GenerateReport(string reportName)
    {
        var timestamp = timeProvider.GetUtcNow().ToString("yyyyMMdd_HHmmss");
        var outputDir = environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("REPORT_OUTPUT_DIR") ?? "/tmp/reports";

        if (!fileSystem.Directory.Exists(outputDir))
            fileSystem.Directory.CreateDirectory(outputDir);

        var reportPath = fileSystem.Path.Combine(outputDir, $"{reportName}_{timestamp}.txt");
        var content = $"Report: {reportName}\nGenerated: {timeProvider.GetUtcNow():O}\nMachine: {environment.MachineName}";

        fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(reportPath, content);
        return reportPath;
    }
}
```

### 5. Testing — fully isolated

```
dotnet add <TestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
dotnet add <TestProject> package Microsoft.Extensions.TimeProvider.Testing
```

```csharp
[Test]
public void GenerateReport_CreatesFileWithExpectedContent()
{
    var fakeTime = new FakeTimeProvider(
        new DateTimeOffset(2026, 1, 15, 12, 0, 0, TimeSpan.Zero));
    var mockFs = new MockFileSystem();
    mockFs.Directory.CreateDirectory("/tmp/reports");
    var env = new FakeEnvironmentProvider(machineName: "TEST-BOX");

    var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs, fakeTime, env);
    var path = generator.GenerateReport("sales");

    Assert.Equal("/tmp/reports/sales_20260115_120000.txt", path);
    Assert.True(mockFs.File.Exists(path));
    Assert.Contains("TEST-BOX", mockFs.File.ReadAllText(path));
}
```

**Key takeaways:** Use `System.IO.Abstractions` for file/directory operations (don't reinvent it), use the built-in `TimeProvider` on .NET 8+, and only write custom wrappers for statics that lack a well-known abstraction. Wrap only the methods you actually call.
